                </span></span></h1></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns"><div class="tei-note"><span xml:lang="en" lang="en" dir="ltr">
                        <span class="tei-persName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/2153">Zacharias</a></span> is a
                        monk who features in <span class="tei-persName"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/74">John of
                            Ephesus'</a></span> Lives of the Eastern Saints. </span><span class="tei-footnote-refs" dir="ltr" lang="en" xml:lang="en"><span class="tei-footnote-ref"><a href="#bib2153-1">1</a></span> </span></div><div style="margin:0 1em 1em; color: #999999;"><small><p><span class="srp-label"><strong>Syriaca.org URI</strong></span>: <span id="syriaca-id"><a href="http://syriaca.org/person/2153">http://syriaca.org/person/2153</a></span></p></small></div></div><div xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" xmlns:local="http://syriaca.org/ns" class="row"><div class="col-md-8"><div class="sources"><h3>Personal Information</h3><h4>Name variant(s): </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-listPerson">
                    <span class="tei-person">
                        <span class="tei-persName">Zacharias</span>
                    </span>
                </span> <a href="/811-1" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Sex: </h4><p class="indent">
                                <span class="tei-persName">Zacharias</span> 
                                was male
                             <a href="/811-2" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><h4>Sanctity: </h4><p class="indent"><span class="tei-persName">Zacharias</span>
                                was a holy person.
                             <a href="/811-3" class="factoid-more"> See factoid page <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Relationships</h3><p class="indent">
                            Zacharias and John of Ephesus 
                            had a close friendship.
                         <a href="/811-4" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">
                            John of Ephesus 
                            commemorated 
                            Zacharias
                            as a holy person.
                         <a href="/811-5" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><p class="indent">
                            Zacharias and Anonymi 3772 
                            were monastics residing in the same monastery.
                         <a href="/811-7" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p></div><div class="sources"><h3>Events</h3><p class="indent">
                            Many miracles came about through the prayers and the bones of Zacharias.
                         <a href="/811-10" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Zacharias pursued the ascetic practice of always keeping a stone in his mouth
                            that kept him from speaking superfluously. Anonymi 3772 followed him in this practice.
                         <a href="/811-6" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Zacharias bound a cord around his hand containing three knots. 
                            The first was to remind him to guard his thoughts. The second was to remind him
                            to keep God in his mind. The third was to remind him to keep the commandments of God.
                         <a href="/811-8" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/><p class="indent">
                            Sworn to secrecy by Zacharias, 
                            John of Ephesus did not reveal his ascetic practices to others until after the saint had died.
                         <a href="/811-9" class="factoid-more">See factoid page
                        <span class="glyphicon glyphicon-circle-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"/></a></p><hr/></div><div class="citation"><h3>How to cite:</h3><span class="element">
